						<summary>

						<p>Door-post of the entrance into the Tirunandikēśvara temple in the village.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Vikramachōḷadēva: Year 20 = 1274-75 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription records a gift of 3 <hi rend="italic">achchu</hi> of money for hot food-offerings to the god Tiru-Anantīśuramuḍaiyār in Kaṇṇāḍipputtūr in Karaivaḻi-nāḍu, by a certain <hi rend="italic">Mūttavāḷ Kaikkōḷa</hi> Kalkōvan-Vīran. The money is stated to have been entrusted to Karikālaśōḻa-bhaṭṭan, a <hi rend="italic">Śivabrāhmaṇa</hi> having right in the temple. It is stated that the investment of the money would yield two <hi rend="italic">kalam</hi> of paddy at every crop-season.</p>						

						</summary>
